\begin_layout Title
Fast Engset computation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Parsiad Azimzadeh, Tommy Carpenter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The 
\emph on
Engset formula
\emph default
 is used to determine the
\emph on
 blocking probability
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 occurring in a queue with a finite number of sources.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is expressed as a fixed point of some function: 
\begin_inset Formula $P=f\left(P\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We provide a proof of the 
\emph on
existence and uniqueness
\emph default
 of this fixed point, showing that the Engset formula is well-posed.
 The literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "iversen2010teletraffic,keshav1997engineering"

\end_inset

 ubiquitously suggests the use of a 
\emph on
fixed point iteration
\emph default
 to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, although it is noted that this procedure may not converge 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "keshav1997engineering"

\end_inset

.
 We give sufficient conditions on convergence (along with examples in which
 convergence does not occur) and demonstrate that it is sometimes outperformed
 by a simple, 
\emph on
unconditionally convergent
\emph default
 
\emph on
bisection method
\emph default
.
 We provide a global convergence result for 
\emph on
Newton's method
\emph default
 and demonstrate that this method converges to the fixed point in just a
 few iterations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Engset formula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
Engset formula
\emph default
 is used to determine the
\emph on
 blocking probability
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 (a.k.a.
 
\emph on
probability of congestion
\emph default
) occurring in a queue with a finite number of sources, such as a telephony
 circuit group.
 In teletraffic engineering, this quantity provides the grade of service
 (GoS): the probability that a new call is rejected because all circuits
 are busy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formula requires that the user knows the 
\emph on
number of servers
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 circuits), the 
\emph on
number of sources
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 callers), and the 
\emph on
offered traffic
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 (the average number of concurrent calls/requests that would have been carried
 if there were an unlimited number of servers).
 The Engset formula is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P=\underbrace{\frac{\binom{S-1}{M}A^{M}}{\sum_{X=0}^{M}\binom{S-1}{X}A^{X}}}_{f\left(P\right)}\text{ where }A=\frac{E}{S-E\left(1-P\right)}.\tag{Engset formula}\label{eq:engset_formula}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 itself is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, it is not straightforward to find a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 that satisfies the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:engset_formula"

\end_inset

.
 It is also not particularly obvious that if such a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 exists, it is unique (the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:engset_formula"

\end_inset

 would not be very useful if it yielded two or more distinct blocking probabilit
ies, or none at all!).
 Existence and uniqueness is established in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:existence_and_uniqueness"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contrast the above with the 
\emph on
Erlang-B formula
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P=\frac{E^{M}/M!}{\sum_{X=0}^{M}E^{X}/X!}.\tag{Erlang-B formula}\label{eq:erlang_b_formula}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Instead of a finite number, the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:erlang_b_formula"

\end_inset

 assumes an infinite number of sources,
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
By taking the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $S\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, the reader can verify that the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:erlang_b_formula"

\end_inset

 is a special case of the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:engset_formula"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 yielding a 
\emph on
Poisson arrival process
\emph default
.
 Most notably, the quantity appearing in the right-hand side of the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:erlang_b_formula"

\end_inset

 does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, and hence computing the blocking probability under the Erlang-B assumption
 is trivial.
\end_layout

