\begin_layout Section
Newton's method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Newton's method
\emph default
 uses first-derivative information to speed up convergence.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P_{0} & \text{ a probability}\nonumber \\
P_{n} & =P_{n-1}-\frac{f\left(P_{n-1}\right)-P_{n-1}}{f^{\prime}\left(P_{n-1}\right)-1}\text{ for }n>0.\tag{Newton's method}\label{eq:newtons_method}
\end{align}

\end_inset

As usual, if 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}\rightarrow P$
\end_inset

 for some probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 the iteration is convergent), 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 satisfies the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:engset_formula"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This follows from taking limits on both sides of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{n}=P_{n-1}-\frac{f\left(P_{n-1}\right)-P_{n-1}}{f^{\prime}\left(P_{n-1}\right)-1}
\]

\end_inset

and using the facts that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuously differentiable and that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}<0$
\end_inset

 on the nonnegative half-line (see the proof of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "thm:existence_and_uniqueness"

\end_inset

 in appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:proofs"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general root-finding problems, strong guarantees regarding convergence
 cannot usually be made about Newton's method (often, convergence results
 for Newton's method are local in nature; i.e.
 for an initial guess 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

 sufficiently close to the solution).
 Therefore, the following nonlocal convergence result---whose proof is given
 in appendix 
\begin_inset Formula $\S$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
