\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:newtons_method"

\end_inset

 outperforms both algorithms by a wide margin, often converging in just
 a few iterations.
 It is difficult to give a tight bound on the number of iterations, so we
 must content ourselves with a rough explanation of the underlying phenomenon.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 denote the fixed point of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{n}=\left|P-P_{n}\right|$
\end_inset

 denote the error at the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th step of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:newtons_method"

\end_inset

.
 It is well-known that if the iterates lies in a sufficiently smal neighbourhood
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon_{n+1}\leq\sup_{Q\in N}\frac{1}{2}\left|\frac{f^{\prime\prime}\left(Q\right)}{f^{\prime}\left(Q\right)-1}\right|\epsilon_{n}^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Indeed, if we assume
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\frac{f^{\prime\prime}\left(Q\right)}{f^{\prime}\left(Q\right)-1}\right|\leq1\label{eq:newtons_method_fast_convergence_assumption}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

